# Graphs {.smaller}


## Scatterplot  {.smaller}


::: {.cell layout-align="center" output-location='default'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="false" code-summary="R" code-line-numbers="true"}
library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
iris <- iris 

ggplot(iris, aes(x=Sepal.Length, y=Sepal.Width, color=Species)) + 
    geom_point(size =2) +   theme_solarized() + 
        labs(title ="My title",
             subtitle = "My subtitle",
             caption = "An explanation about the graph",
             x = "My title for the x-axis (suggestion: Sepal Length)",
             y = "Sepal Width")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](part_O2_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-1-1.png){fig-align='center' width=960}
:::
:::




## Scatterplot  {.smaller}


The same thing with a different pair of variables, but now I am including the linear relationship between the variables.



::: {.cell layout-align="center" output-location='default'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="false" code-summary="R" code-line-numbers="true"}
ggplot(iris, aes(x=Petal.Length, y=Petal.Width)) + 
    geom_point(size =2) +   theme_solarized() +
   geom_point(aes(color = Species))+
   geom_smooth(method='lm')
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](part_O2_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-2-1.png){fig-align='center' width=960}
:::
:::




## Scatterplot  {.smaller}


I could  include a linear relationship by group. In all cases, we observe a positive relationship between the variables, but the relationship seens stonger in `versicolor`.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" output-location='default'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="false" code-summary="R" code-line-numbers="true"}
ggplot(iris, aes(x=Petal.Length, y=Petal.Width, color = Species)) + 
    geom_point(size =2) +   theme_solarized() +
   geom_point(aes(color = Species))+
   geom_smooth(method='lm')
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](part_O2_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png){fig-align='center' width=960}
:::
:::



## Boxplot  {.smaller}

I could also create boxplots using the `iris` dataset. Notice there is one observation with very low Length in the `virginica` group.


::: {.cell layout-align="center" output-location='default'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="false" code-summary="R" code-line-numbers="true"}
ggplot(iris, aes(Species, Sepal.Length, fill=Species)) + 
  geom_boxplot()+ theme_solarized() + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks= seq(0,30, by=.5)) 
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](part_O2_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-4-1.png){fig-align='center' width=960}
:::
:::





## Density plots  {.smaller}

Here is a nice-looking density plot.



::: {.cell layout-align="center" output-location='default'}

```{.r .cell-code  code-fold="false" code-summary="R" code-line-numbers="true"}
 ggplot(iris, aes(x=Petal.Length, colour=Species, fill=Species)) +
  geom_density(alpha=.3) + theme_solarized()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](part_O2_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-5-1.png){fig-align='center' width=960}
:::
:::






